      "content": "The history of unionization in the US is a story of labor rights being systematically eroded by corporate interests, with the 1935 National Labor Relations Act (NLRA) being a crucial turning point in the fight for workers' rights. The NLRA established the right to collective bargaining, but subsequent laws like the Taft-Hartley Act of 1947 and the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (ERISA) have been used to weaken union power. Today, union membership has declined to around 10% of the workforce, with many workers facing anti-union tactics and laws like \"right-to-work\" laws that restrict collective bargaining.",
